## Connecting Real Integrations

### üîµ Slack Setup

1. **Go to** [api.slack.com/apps](https://api.slack.com/apps) ‚Üí **Create New App** ‚Üí **From scratch**
2. **Name**: `FlowGuard` ‚Üí select your workspace
3. **OAuth & Permissions** ‚Üí Add these **Bot Token Scopes**:
   - `channels:history`, `channels:read`, `chat:write`, `reactions:read`, `users:read`
4. **Event Subscriptions** ‚Üí Enable ‚Üí Set Request URL:
   - `https://<your-tunnel-url>/webhooks/slack/events`
   - Subscribe to: `message.channels`, `reaction_added`, `reaction_removed`
5. **Interactivity** ‚Üí Enable ‚Üí Request URL: `https://<your-tunnel-url>/webhooks/slack/actions`
6. **Install to Workspace** ‚Üí Copy **Bot Token** and **Signing Secret**
7. **Update [.env](file:///Users/adrianyeo/FlowGuard/.env)**:
   ```
   SLACK_BOT_TOKEN=xoxb-your-bot-token
   SLACK_SIGNING_SECRET=your-signing-secret
   SLACK_CLIENT_ID=your-client-id
   SLACK_CLIENT_SECRET=your-client-secret
   ```

### üü¢ Jira Setup

1. **Go to** [developer.atlassian.com/console/myapps](https://developer.atlassian.com/console/myapps/)
2. **Create** ‚Üí OAuth 2.0 integration ‚Üí Name: `FlowGuard`
3. **Permissions** ‚Üí Jira ‚Üí Add `read:jira-work`, `write:jira-work`
4. **Settings** ‚Üí Callback URL: `https://<your-tunnel-url>/webhooks/jira/oauth/callback`
5. **Webhooks** ‚Üí Create webhook at your Jira admin:
   - URL: `https://<your-tunnel-url>/webhooks/jira`
   - Events: `jira:issue_created`, `jira:issue_updated`
   - Generate a **webhook secret** and add to [.env](file:///Users/adrianyeo/FlowGuard/.env):
   ```
   JIRA_WEBHOOK_SECRET=your-jira-webhook-secret
   JIRA_CLOUD_ID=your-cloud-id
   JIRA_BASE_URL=https://your-org.atlassian.net
   ```

### üü° GitHub Setup

1. **Go to** GitHub ‚Üí Settings ‚Üí Developer Settings ‚Üí **GitHub Apps** ‚Üí New
2. **Name**: `FlowGuard`, **Homepage**: `http://localhost:5173`
3. **Webhook URL**: `https://<your-tunnel-url>/webhooks/github`
4. **Webhook secret**: Generate one, add to [.env](file:///Users/adrianyeo/FlowGuard/.env) as `GITHUB_WEBHOOK_SECRET`
5. **Permissions**:
   - Repository: Pull requests (Read & Write), Issues (Read & Write)
   - Subscribe to: `pull_request`, `pull_request_review`, `issues`
6. **Generate private key** ‚Üí Save as `github-private-key.pem`
7. **Update [.env](file:///Users/adrianyeo/FlowGuard/.env)**:
   ```
   GITHUB_APP_ID=your-app-id
   GITHUB_WEBHOOK_SECRET=your-webhook-secret
   GITHUB_PRIVATE_KEY_PATH=./github-private-key.pem
   ```

### üöÄ Getting the Tunnel URL

Run the tunnel script to get a public URL for your webhooks:
```bash
npm run tunnel
```
This starts a `cloudflared` tunnel and outputs a URL like `https://abc-xyz.trycloudflare.com`.
Use this URL in the webhook configurations above.

> **Note**: The URL changes each time you restart the tunnel (free tier). The tunnel script auto-updates Slack/GitHub webhook URLs if you add `SLACK_APP_CONFIG_TOKEN`, `SLACK_APP_ID` to [.env](file:///Users/adrianyeo/FlowGuard/.env).

